gression has occurred, can be too late. And I am not just referring to abuse. I think the author has chosen to focus on abuse to get the knee jerkers jumping on her bandwagon. What I think is equally important, and what is a major purpose of such control, is to ensure that a suitable education is provided. &#10;I agree that the state should not demand that you teach their curriculum, but they should demand that you teach a well rounded curriculum not just based on your priorities, but which is objective and broad enough to give the child the tools to be able to choose. A child will not necessarily develop in the parents image. If a child has not received an education which provides it with formal qualifications then it is deprived of the most important thing of all ? choice. Choice to follow certain career paths which, however in contrary to the parents desires, may be what the child wants. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1199" language="en" documentId="957" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="richesrant" date="06 November 2009 8:03pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6748324" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="957" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="14"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="15" end="239"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="240" end="607"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="608" end="1199"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>